    "body": "@davidkna, \r\n\r\nFor the redundant conda env name, `conda config --set changeps1 False` works. Thanks a lot. But the conda icon does not appear yet.\r\n\r\nFollowing is the output of `starship explain`:\r\n```\r\n  ~/workspace/dotfiles on  main [$1!3]                                                                         via 🅒 nemd  16:26:38\r\n❯ starship explain\r\n Here's a breakdown of your prompt:\r\n \"❯ \" (<1ms)                     -  A character (usually an arrow) beside where the text is entered in your terminal\r\n \"via 🅒 nemd \" (<1ms)            -  The current conda environment, if $CONDA_DEFAULT_ENV is set\r\n \"~/workspace/dotfiles \" (<1ms)  -  The current working directory\r\n \" \" (<1ms)                      -  Fills the remaining space on the line with a pad string\r\n \"on  main \" (<1ms)             -  The active branch of the repo in your current directory\r\n \"[$1!3] \" (3ms)                 -  Symbol representing the state of the repo\r\n \"  \" (36ms)                    -  The current operating system\r\n \" 16:30:04\" (<1ms)             -  The current local time\r\n```\r\n\r\nI set CONDA_DEFAULT_ENV=\"base\" and reload the starship config. But the conda module does not show any info on the line at all in this case. So, setting CONDA_DEFAULT_ENV would not be helpful. Plus, I do not want to activate default conda env to avoid mis-installation of packages. I believe some people would prefer this style too. \r\n\r\nIs there any difference in loading symbols between the modules?",
